/-
  Data.PDF.Content.GlyphList — the Adobe Glyph List

  Ports `Pdf.Content.GlyphList` from Hackage's `pdf-toolbox-content`
  (https://github.com/Yuras/pdf-toolbox, `content/lib/Pdf/Content/GlyphList.hs`,
  fetched from
  `https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Yuras/pdf-toolbox/master/content/lib/Pdf/Content/GlyphList.hs`),
  module 4 of the `pdf-toolbox-content` import documented in
  `docs/imports/PdfToolboxContent/dependencies.md`.

  The Adobe Glyph List (AGL) is a fixed table mapping PostScript/PDF glyph
  names (e.g. `"Aacute"`) to the Unicode code point they represent, used when
  extracting text from PDFs whose fonts use named glyphs rather than direct
  character codes. It is pure data: a ~4280-entry literal table with no
  behaviour to port, so it is transcribed verbatim from upstream's
  `Map.fromList` literal rather than re-derived.

  ## Design

  Upstream represents the table as `Map ByteString Char`; this port uses
  `Std.HashMap Data.ByteString Char` (`Data.ByteString` is the already-ported
  `linen` slice-based byte string, reused rather than re-declared). Upstream's
  table has no duplicate keys, so `Std.HashMap.ofList`'s right-biased
  (last-wins) duplicate resolution never comes into play — no `.reverse`
  trick is needed here (contrast `Data.PDF.Content.UnicodeCMap`, whose parsed
  tables can have upstream-meaningful duplicates).
-/
import Linen.Data.ByteString
import Linen.Data.Text.Encoding
import Std.Data.HashMap

-- The literal table below has ~4280 entries; elaborating it as one large
-- list literal exceeds Lean's default recursion depth.
set_option maxRecDepth 40000

namespace Data.PDF.Content.GlyphList

open Data.Text.Encoding (encodeUtf8)

/-- The Adobe Glyph List table, mapping glyph names to Unicode characters, as a
